The world of commercial video game journalism consists of multiple specializations. We have the typical game reviews usually done by IGN or Metacritic, which assign a score to video games after people on their teams play through them. We have video game news sites like GameSpot, which provide news on the latest happenings in the video game space. Finally, we have a less discussed area of video game journalism that is arguably more important than the others: Player Culture. 

Every person who plays video games has a story and reason for doing what they love, and covering player culture involves exploring the motivations of what led them to pursue gaming as a hobby or a career. Many of these individuals don’t get their flowers even when they achieve amazing feats in their respective areas. A video game area where this is usually the norm is speedrunning. 

Speedrunning is the practice of completing a video game as quickly as possible, often using planned routes and exploiting glitches to save time. It consists of a massive, extremely active community of gamers who spend hours and hours trying to complete video games as quickly as possible, often without getting any attention other than their name on a website and the satisfaction of their own community. 

Over the years, this website's name has changed, and it often depends on the game. It is hard to centralize everything in one place, so it is so hard to note these amazing feats when they happen. Additionally, big game journalist studios do not care to acknowledge these players, as they do not give them the numbers compared to reviewing the next big AAA game. 

Over the past few years, we have seen a shift in this culture as speedrunning has become more popular than ever, which could be due to one creator entering the speedrunning scene and changing it forever.

Eight years ago, a YouTube channel named Summoning Salt posted a video of a speedrun attempt of Mike Tyson’s punch-out. The video wasn’t impressive or even a world record, but the player's dedication to the game was evident as Summoning Salt continued posting speed runs.

Eventually, his content began to change and slowly grow in quality, and eventually, he would post a video titled “World Record Progression: Mike Tyson.” This was his analysis of the world record for the game he had been playing. The video grew extremely popular, holding 1.5 million views to this day.

This video wasn’t even that impressive. The editing was shotty, the analysis did not have many player testimonials, and his scriptwriting had some work to do. But it did bring attention to Punch Out, and while he didn’t know it then, Summoning Salt would have an impact far beyond himself.

It was clear Summoning Salt had much to learn; he was not even close to stopping his journey into speedrunning. His next video would soon come, covering a different game, “Super Mario Bros,” a game known by everyone, and the video started to garner attention. The video now holds 2.4 million views on YouTube despite being made 7 years ago. 

This video did something amazing. It spotlighted players who have lived their lives chasing numbers on a website. Summoning Salt would talk about these players extremely fondly, praising their efforts and telling their stories, something larger corporations wouldn’t dare to do. 

And as his videos improved, so did his testimonials' quality. Summoning Salt would eventually begin interviewing these players, giving them a platform to talk about the games they have been speedrunning and how they achieved the world record. A good example of this would be in his video covering Super Mario 64 blind speedrunning, where he interviewed Bubzia, who helped Summoning Salt create the video and give a new perspective to the audience, along with educating Summoning Salt on the intricacies of a speedrun.

Creators like Summoning Salt are extremely important for these smaller communities of speedrunners. They help bring thousands of people who watch the videos to try speed runs themselves, and I have even been tempted myself as the journey a certain speed run takes to develop is fascinating.
